social_posts.post_text: The Stories We Tell

Reality Bytes

#stablediffusion

遺忘

So many of my posts have to do with time. Memories. Forgetting things. Time. I spend a lot of time time-traveling when I retouch images. Literally on multiple planes. 1) playing with the element of time by changing the way the original image was shot 2) floating into the past and reliving random memories that have no obvious meaning/value or relation to the image I’m retouching. This one’s harder to explain but I sometimes get dislocated from time when I retouch. Probably has something to do with the meditative nature of the work. I sometimes relive a scene from the past quite vividly; standing in line at a McDonald’s in Barcelona… walking to my car with my friends coming out of an AMC. Nothing particularly special about those memories. Just random flashbacks. Probably has something to do with the way my brain works. 

Or probably just that I’m crazy 😜

#gnarlsbarkley

I wish

This is one of my favorite pictures. @carleydeckr and I had gone to the Oceano Dunes Natural Preserve State Park on a cloudy day. Not my preference for weather, but when you got lemons as a photographer you are still expected to make a Rembrandt masterpiece. 

This would have been the third or fourth time I’d shot sand dunes. The thing with sand dunes is that they’re terribly particular. It’s hard to find clean sand without shrubbery or trees. It’s even harder not to muck up that sand with footprints. Sand dunes without retouching is pointless.

So we’d gotten to the dunes with this red cloth. The red cloth is real. I can’t remember exactly how long it was but it was very long. I’d gotten it from one of the fabric stores in DTLA where I had my old studio. For this shot to work however the cloth needed tension which means it needed to be anchored down out of frame so I held it with my left hand while shooting with my right hand. With a little bit of luck we got the breeze we needed. And of course Carley was perfect.

But alas, the shot was dreary and blue from the clouds casting (literally) blue onto the the sand. It was not the shot I had envisioned but it was the best we could get that day.

Until generative AI. 

The frame is now bigger. More sand. More red cloth. More majestic. The new picture is actually 73% bigger (in pixels) than the original image. And the weather while still not perfect (I would have preferred more backlight halo around my subject) is much more preferable to the original overcast day. Everything else works. It’s not perfect. I played around with at least 15 iterations of the sky here in Photoshop Beta and another 30 or so in stable diffusion before settling on this final backdrop. Admittedly it’s not that you can actually get ANYTHING you want. It’s more that you can get something close and you have to work with it. And it still requires an extensive amount of post-processing to make it work well. 

More on this later.

@carleydeckr

social_posts.post_text:
Avedonesque

I suppose it’s just as serendipitous as catching lighting in a bottle.

I would have never shot this image this way. Hairlight, rim light, front light… it’s a lot of lights. Nor would I haul a bed into the studio. Maybe a couch. Never a bed. Admittedly I’ve only ever thought of Richard Avedon as a hero but not an actual style I’d actually attempt to emulate. 

Never shot two girls. Not nude at least. Not that I couldn’t. Just that I wouldn’t. Too hard to manage one much less two models at a time. Historically they fight for attention and that stresses me out. Even if I did shoot two nude girls at the same time, girls kissing girls doesn’t do it for me. It wouldn’t be a pose I’d request.

But upon prompting the stable diffusion for 1 girl, it gave me two girls back-to-back, which led to hugging, which led to kissing, which led to the beginning of this picture. From that point on it was a matter of redrawing virtually (pun intended) every single detail you can imagine. From the teeth, to the conjoined lips, to the missing arms, to the misshapen fingers, to downsizing the unusually large breasts, to the misplaced earring, and more that I can’t even remember. I realized two things: 1) text to image is really a process of trial and error. It took about 10 hours to generate and retouch this image. 2) I don’t know what ears look like IRL.

Realistically this is as close to Avedonesque as I’ll ever get. And strangely it’s one of the favorite pictures I’ve ever created. Or should I say “we’ve” ever created. Might have to change my pronoun now.

#stablediffusion

攝影師（尤其是亞洲攝影師）討厭在直射陽光下拍攝。他們說光線太刺眼，但我認為這只是因為他們不知道如何控制光線（或修飾圖像）。

我喜歡直射的陽光。我喜歡直射陽光在皮膚上製造出的高光效果。我喜歡它所創造出來的對比度。我喜歡身體上的陰影。我喜歡透過照片感受到直射陽光帶來的溫暖。加上偶爾的汗水閃爍。這是一種直觀的感受。

對於那些問我是否能拍攝亞洲模特的人，這就是我的預設答案。是的，我不僅可以拍攝亞洲模特，而且可以保持我的風格並拍攝亞洲模特。我拒絕遵從當地使用無聊和平面照明或僅在陰影中拍攝的標準。如果你沒有什麼可隱藏的，就站在光線中吧。

這就是我的訊息所在。我挑戰你做你自己。不要隨波逐流。不要妥協。不要屈服於社會、文化、教育和/或宗教所創造的極權主義規範。你的命運只屬於你自己。不要把你的命運託付給任何其他人或事物。我向你保證，如果你對自己的生活不滿意，上述的任何一個系統都不會為你流淚。對自己的生活負責，按照自己的規則生活。

Photographers (especially Asian photographers) hate shooting with direct sunlight. They say the lighting too harsh but I honestly think it is because they don’t know how to control the light (or retouch the images. 

I love direct sunlight. I love the highlights against the skin. I love the contrast it creates. I love the shadows on the body. I love the warmth direct sunlight creates that can be felt through the photograph. The occasional glisten of sweat. It’s visceral. 

For those that ask me if I can shoot Asian models let this be my default answer. Yes, not only can I shoot Asian models, I can retain my style and *still* shoot Asian models. I refuse to conform to the local standards of using boring and flat lighting or only shoot in the shade. If you have nothing to hide, stand in the light. 😉 

Therein lies my message. I challenge you to be you. Don’t conform. Don’t negotiate. Don’t yield to fascist norms created by society, culture, education and/or religion. Your destiny is yours and yours alone. Do not entrust or yield your destiny to anyone/anything else. I assure you that none of the aforementioned systems will cry if you are unhappy with your life. Take responsibility for your own life and live by your own rules. 

@ainslee_wang

social_posts.post_text:
This is how I look out the window too

@ziiickyvicky

Must climb ladder…

As a photographer I can’t help but make models climb stuff. Stairs. Ladders. Chairs. Rocks. Trees. It’s an pre-programmed response. Not sure where it comes from. Most likely boredom. Or maybe just to see if they’ll do it and how the shot turns out. Fortunately no one has gotten hurt in the process… so far 😂

Hepburnesque

I could never be a photojournalist. Ilike retouching too much and the last time I checked, photojournalists weren't allowed to doctor their photos. 

So when this picture came out of stable diffusion I didn’t know what to think. Honestly I wasn’t even sure what I was looking at. Granted it was conceived out of words so I shouldn’t have been so surprised. It started with something I'd drawn on a box of Godiva chocolates on my desk. But this was not the layout. Yet this was much more captivating than the original idea. Something about a naked Audrey Hepburn (I dunno why her) marching against social constructs. But my sketch didn't have bodyguards. And it was supposed to be a clash. Not a march together. So understandably it took time for me to wrap my head around this new rendition. But this version made more sense and ironically felt more familiar than what I had originally envisioned. 

So layer by layer it came to be. Fixing the girls' expressions and their matching "wardrobe". Fixing the bodyguards' matching suits. Fixing all the faces in the background. And then there was the signage. Stable diffusion can’t actually make real words because it doesn’t actually know language (AFAIK) so all the signs were gibberish. And I had no idea what they were protesting against so I left this challenge for the very end. But since this image was a reflection of me I thought that this image should be significant and make a statement. I pondered this question a bit before realizing I would again have to censor out all the nipples in order to share this image on Instagram. And as I let out a "Fuck that" in response to that thought I realized I might just have something to say. 
 
So the final layer is the middle finger to the platform that I’ve chosen to showcase my artistry. The love-hate relationship with pretty much the most restrictive and worst format to showcase photography. Whether it’s aspect ratio, algorithms or censorship. Yet it’s unfortunately still the only game in town so if you’re going to play, you’ve got to play by their rules. But I can play within the rules and still express my discontent…

At least until I get reported and banned 😝

Hair commercials

@muguang.arts

Beach Dreams

Some of my favorite shoots have been at Malibu. Waiting for the sun to get low enough over the water to create that warmer color temperature (not quite sunset). The breeze that kicks up in the afternoon and creates that afternoon “chop” that surfers hate. Finding a little cover to break up the sunlight and the scenery so it looks like you’re somewhere really far away from home. Malibu’s smaller beaches are great for this you’re willing to climb a little here and there. El Matador, El Pescador, and La Piedra are ones I still know like the back of my hand. I even surfed La Piedra once.

I haven’t been to Malibu for years. 

So this is a tribute to the shoot that I would’ve had had I gone to Malibu. In all of the “model testing” that I have done in stable diffusion I have attempted to retain my aesthetic and get as close as I can to obtaining that LUCIMA look. This image is no different as it is stylistically as close to what I would’ve done if I had shot it in real life, minus the model. 

But with AI there is always the element of surprise. Not everything goes your way when you’re attempting to go from text to image. And the iterations required in order to get an image that’s (barely) acceptable is frustrating at best. This is why I believe that as advanced as it is, AI is not quite there yet. It requires a strong hand of control and deep knowledge of prompts. And with a platform such as stable diffusion, you are really tested to demonstrate your ability to manipulate the machine. It’s so modular that you have to really get deep into checkpoints, loras, and all the fine controls. At best it still feels like a slot machine and you really don’t know what you will get. You must be open-minded and willing to work with the results, sometimes hours post-processing the results. And if you’re lucky and really put in the work you might just get a worthy result. 

Oh and drawing in the shoestring holes you and the lacing on the top was a pain in the ass. 

#stablediffusion #AI
Malibu Nights

When is enough, enough?

This image has gone through more iterations than I’d like to admit. But the final iteration is the one that I question the most.

After I had posted this picture on my IG Stories, I showed it to a co-worker who declared that the hand on the chair bothered her. That rattled in my head for a bit because I didn’t notice the hand until she mentioned it but it was too late since I had already posted it to Stories.

On a whim yesterday I decided to ask my broadcast channel (thanks guys!) if the hand was a problem. More than half of you guys said yes.

I agreed. 

So I went back to Photoshop Beta and fixed it.

So what’s the problem?

I have a problem with me asking others what they think about my pictures. But beyond that, when is enough, enough? I could have stopped at my own eyes and decided “This is enough. I don’t want to do any more”. Or I could have polled a thousand strangers and tallied their list of problems to resolve in the image. Hell, maybe they find 10 other issues with the image I hadn’t seen before. 

So the question becomes, “When is enough, enough?”

When do you stop shooting that extra frame? When do you stop retouching? When do you post that picture on IG?

I dunno. Personally I think the buck stops with me so I’m responsible for it all, good or bad. But sometimes I make mistakes like letting a poorly positioned hand slip through the cracks? So maybe I need a little feedback here and there?

But I hate to think that I actually need the feedback from others (*gasp* you mean to tell me I’m not perfect? 😂 )

Am I crazy to think this way? Wait, don’t answer that. No seriously, am I?

PS. The hand is now anatomically incorrect as it is missing a thumb. It was the best Photoshop’s AI could do with regenerating a hand. Now does that bother you like it bothers me???

Attention to Detail

These are two pieces that I’m inclined to bring to life. I’m not a fashion designer by trade but I’m hoping this creates opportunities to collaborate with other creatives. Suggestions welcome! I’ll be back in Taipei end of July so preferably someone local but I imagine we could work remotely on this as well. Lemme know!

Oh and the conversation here continues on my broadcast channel. Link in profile. Cheers!

⁣Mixed⁣
⁣
I have mixed feelings about this image. So far playing at the fringe of Midjourney and Stable Diffusion I haven’t yet noticed just how much we “overlap”. It’s not so much a fear of being displaced (although that exists too) but rather this eerie feeling that this image which feels so familiar, wasn’t one that I actually shot. In fact I didn’t even prompt for it. I pulled the original off a general server (open rights) and then modified it with Stable Diffusion and Photoshop. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
This image resonates with me because it looks like something I would have actually shot. It started out as a girl sitting in the sand against the sun wearing a full dress. I didn’t like her top nor did I like the sand that had been trampled on so I modified both, along with her hair and face. When finished editing, I couldn’t help but feel like it was my creation and yet also wasn’t my creation. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I guess I have a problem with ownership. I like owning the process front to back. I learned how to do basic makeup for this reason. I like getting my hands dirty and doing things myself. So when AI comes along and lends a (BIG) helping hand, being the greedy person that I am, I take it first no questions asked and later start wondering why I feel I cheated or tainted my process. I mean it’s not a question of rights but rather ownership.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
But then again I depend on Sony to make my camera. I depend on the lab to develop my film (though I scan it!). I depend on the models to come with their good looks and their sparkling personalities. So there are plenty of my workflow that I can not control.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Except that I am now yielding so much control over the image creation to Midjourney and Stable Diffusion. And being the control freak that I am, I’m having a hard time reconciling my feelings. Is it that simple? Just a question of letting go? I can’t be the only one?

Tenet Nosce

This was a picture I made a couple weeks back. For the record I’ve only been messing around with generative AI for a couple weeks. As one could have predicted it became a deep dive into uncharted waters.

And in the process I can’t help but think I’m getting to know myself better. 

If you could have anything you want, what would you ask for? Understandably I see a lot of people attempt to make what is the equivalent of porn with Midjourney and Stable Diffusion (hereafter MJ and SD). Hell a lot of people call my stuff porn too. But I’m a little more curious about my own processes and what’s below the surface… 

After the initial dive into “let’s see what SD can do…” I’ve moved towards “what would I have done if I could have…” or “what could I not do IRL that would have been really cool”. Those questions have driven my more recent creations. 

Case in point, what does a transparent latex skin suit look like? (One of my earlier and admittedly more primitive questions for SD 😂)

I am curious to know how you guys view these tools and how they are helping further your journey?

PS. First to comment what movie the post title references wins a chicken dinner. No googling! 😂 

PPS. This was SD plus Photoshop. This was pre-MJ for me.

Note to self: Return to Paris

Midjourney x Stable Diffusion x Photoshop x IG

For Display Purposes Only

Now back to our regularly scheduled programming… again.

Join in the conversation on my broadcast at channel. Link in profile lucimablog2.0. 

#rh #waterfalltable #showcase #incaseofemergency

Brigitte x floral

Made this short video with all the iterations of Brigitte x floral to demonstrate the iterations that an image goes through. The process is heavily truncated for to keep the video short and because I didn’t keep track of every little change the image I made 😝. For example it took me some 20+ iterations of Midjourney just to settle on this image. Once I decided on the image it was a matter of fixing and enhancing this image with the same logic my normal images go through. Using Stable Diffusion I altered the top of the dress into something a little more LUCIMAesque. Along with fixing the fingers, the fingers, hands, lips, nose shadow, breasts, and top. What the video doesn’t show are the multiple iterations that I went through in Photoshop just to get parts of the picture right. 

So ultimately this is a collaborative effort. Starting with an idea via Midjourney and then using Stable Diffusion and Photoshop and sometimes back into Midjourney to refine the idea. 

At least one person has suggested I make this into a tutorial. While there are plenty of tutorial videos on how to use MJ, SD, PS I’m sure there are few if any that go into such detail about how it becomes an integrated workflow. The thing is such a video sits atop on an existing workflow. One that integrates multiple tools already (pre-AI). So in order to teach this workflow, I would need to first teach the logic that is the foundation for the process; a logic that is more philosophical in nature and less 1-2-3. Does this make any sense to anyone other than just me?

TLDR: I’m probably not making a YouTube tutorial.

What’s real?

Truth is if we were honest to ourselves, we have been moving away from reality for a long time. Even before AI there was Facetune. And before Facetune there was already Photoshop. And before digital we were already dodging and burning our images on film. And before that we were still wearing makeup and altering our appearances for thousands of years…

So what’s with the backlash against AI generated images?

Well for one, I feel less and less involved in the making of the images. It’s just so different. The weight of the process of creation is so heavy on the design (and while some call it quits after they get something from Midjourney, the process for me is also heavy on the black-end/retouching). But gone is the middle part. All that execution stuff. All the “how it’s made” stuff. It does make me feel less important. It certainly makes my models feel less important. Yes I’m still directing the model, modifying the lighting and negotiating the background, but it’s just keystrokes now. Gone is all the know how that made these pictures come to life in the old-fashioned way. 

Gone is the human element. I’m not even sure if that’s a pun or just a middle finger straight to the face. 

So yeah does it matter how it’s made? Of course it does. Or is this the future of “how it’s made”? I don’t know man. I don’t know what’s real and what’s not anymore. 

Midjourney was not involved in the process of making these images. 

#stablediffusion #reality #potd #whyamihashtagging #shadowbanned

social_posts.post_text:
LUCIMA vs. AI

Midjourney can’t do this… yet. 

I’ve always wanted to show before and after pics like this but have always feared the repercussions of showing the pre-processed image. 

1) for fear that people would pass judgement on the model not being perfect. 
2) for fear that people would pass judgement on me for picking imperfect models. 

I know it sounds ridiculous when you say it out loud but mostly posting before pics makes me look good but makes the model look bad. 

Unless she doesn’t have feelings.

Which is the case in this Stable Diffusion-only generated image. I got a really strong portrait out of SD but it wasn’t perfect. (Not even AI can be perfect. So dunno why we as humans aspire for perfection. That’s another topic.) Anyway, sent it over to Photoshop and applied the LUCIMA “filter”. I say filter in parentheses because it’s a mental filter of how I think a face should look. Where the eyes should be. Where the nose should be. How the cheekbones and jawline and features should look. There’s no magic button that does all of this. It’s all manually done with liquefy in PS. And therefore can not be replicated…

Yet. 

But this is my version of reality. All my pics endure this treatment. It’s why they all have my visual signature. 

Too much? Perhaps. It’s not for everyone. It’s mine and mine alone. But you’re more than welcome to tell me if I “missed a spot”. I tried to retain as many flaws as possible (ironically) to increase the sense of realism. 

TLDR: Please stop asking me for the model’s IG. She’s not real.

Just can’t tell anymore…

@ana.rinee

A Dose of Reality

Can you tell if this image is real or not? Because I can’t tell anymore. I mean I shot it so I know. But generally speaking, I guess it didn’t take long for AI generated images to catch up to reality. Part of me wonders if maybe we didn’t subconsciously will this to happen… that we secretly wanted to be fed into the Matrix. I mean we say we don’t want it but yet we keep making technologies that bring us closer and closer to that reality. Don’t kill the messenger. 

For the record this image is real. But I’ll admit it’s harder and harder for my pictures to aesthetically compete with the ones generated by MJ and SD. I said aesthetically. Lemme repeat. Aesthetically. It’s like how your real life can’t compete with the highlight reel generator that is Instagram. One is fake and glorious. The other is real and meh. I mean do you really wanna post a pic of yourself eating that cheeseburger?

The diehards (and blowhards) will complain that Instagram isn’t real life and real life trumps all. And yet we argue right here on IG (through their screens) about the dangers of technology and AI. So what are you doing here if not taking advantage of (and being taken advantage of by) technology and AI? You too are dependent on the technology that gives you these dopamine hits via hot girls, likes and comments. Because whether you can see it or not technology and AI are already in your life. 

Again I’m not here to tell you how to think or what to think. That’s your prerogative. Just don’t kid yourself about the extent our lives are dependent on technology and AI.

And then there were horses…

#thatsallfolks

You guys tired of horses yet? 😂 

#nowhere #noone #notreal #noig #nomidjourney

#stablediffusion

Fields of Gold

#stablediffusion

Consolidation

The last 6 weeks have been interesting. I’m currently flying over the Pacific Ocean but while on vacation with the family I’ve had some time play around with text-to-image AI. I started out experimenting with Stable Diffusion in the end of May, tried creating my own model on Google Collab, and eventually tried Midjourney. But after two months I’ve really come full circle. While having different tools at my disposal has been awesome, my current hybridized workflow really involves more of Stable Diffusion and the tools at my disposal.

Case in point, this picture has a story. It was inspired by a real picture by the beautiful @bianca_richards (go check out her page). While we have never had the opportunity to shoot, we follow each other here on IG. I really liked her silhouette and the image triggered a question; What if there were a nude model window shopping looking at a naked mannequin? Most of my ideas start out as a random question like that. Particularly with AI-generated images, they tend to be questions I couldn’t ask in real life because obviously we couldn’t shoot on the street or in a mall naked. So I started with Bianca’s reference image and started playing around with altering the environment. I need a mannequin in the display. I also preferred a mall setting vs. a street setting. This particular image (while not the most realistic) took me a couple days to get to its final state. And while there are many little details in this image that leave me wanting more, it really pushed me to demonstrate my control of Stable Diffusion using outside reference images, compositing in Photoshop, prompting for the changes I want, using ControlNet to hold certain elements constant, increasing resolution, and inpainting the problems away, and then more Photoshop. That’s currently my basic workflow.

Ligers

From the top let’s talk about how ridiculous this picture is. 

1. That’s a Liger. Yeah the kind from Napoleon Dynamite (when you crossbreed a lion with a tiger). I asked for one and this is what Midjourney thinks is a liger. Since I’ve never seen one it’s as good as gold to me 😂 

2. That girl is riding a liger. Not sure PETA or ASPCA would approve. Not to mention I think this would be really dangerous (umm Siegfried and Roy?) I mean is there a harness? Is it trained? That’s one mean looking liger. 

3. But it’s fashionable. She’s wearing a couture dress… and the liger is wearing a frilly… wait a second, is that the same dress? Wtf? They’re both part of the same outfit? How would you even get the liger into that dress? This takes animals as fashion accessories to a whole ‘nother level.

In all seriousness, I find that one of the greatest values of AI-generated imagery is that it extends the realm of “what is possible”. Whether it’s riding ligers in the same dress or three Audrey Hepburns protesting Instagram censorship, AI opens my imagination up to previously unthinkable and (for all intents and purposes) ridiculous ideas. 

Otherwise we would just shoot this stuff in real life 😊

Hero

The last 5 days have been wild. Stable Diffusion released SDXL1.0 5 days ago and I spent the next several days (in Shanghai) troubleshooting all the problems with SDXL1.0 running on Automatic1111, because let’s face it… this stuff doesn’t always work LOL.

If this sounds like gibberish it’s because it is gibberish to 99% of the photography population. Not everyone is going to make the switch from digital to AI and even less will use Stable Diffusion so I’m really speaking to a very small subset of the photography community.

But then again 99% of the photography population wouldn’t understand me talking about how Lightroom blurred the line with Photoshop by introducing the power of masks (a while ago now)… because not everyone made the switch from film to digital.

And going just a little farther back, 99% of the photography population won't understand how scanning film was an art form in and of itself because even at max resolution, I was either limited by the scanner or limited by the size of the film… because not everyone scanned their own film.

And just like that we have covered the last three eras of photography; film, digital, and now AI. Within the 20 years (give or take a few years) we’ve seen technology advance at a logarithmic pace. And to be honest it’s hard to keep up. Learning the AI interfaces requires more than just downloading Discord and paying Midjourney for a subscription because let's face it, Midjourney is child’s play compared to Stable Diffusion in terms of controls.

And once you open the bag of worms that is Stable Diffusion, you’re knee-deep in the command prompt faster than you can say “WTF”. But I assure you that’s where the promised land lies.

Ghost in the Shell

I joined Model Mayhem when I first started taking pictures back in 2009. It was at the time the only site to connect with others in the industry for photoshoots and since I had no experience taking pictures (besides myself and my dog) I signed up and began messaging amateur models to shoot.

I had grand ideas about how well things would turn out. I began by messaging each model with a custom-tailored idea about how her look would be awesome for some specific idea. That changed quickly as I realized the low response rate made my ROI very low and precluded the possibility of coming up with unique ideas for every model. So I started copying and pasting canned messages. 

As I began to achieve some success shooting better models I lowered my initial time investment for each shoot. I did more “testing” and reserved my time for bigger projects and only for my favorite (and more importantly dependable) models. Working with new people was always hit or miss. Hell working with models I’d already shot before was hit or miss. Plenty of times I would be left sitting in the studio (or in the car) twiddling my thumbs, chatting with the makeup artist and stylist. 

As time went on I got more and more jaded and less and less willing to invest in shoots. I started doing basic makeup myself so I wouldn’t need a makeup artist, I started asking models bring their own clothes so I wouldn’t need a stylist, and I sometimes double-booked models on the same day with the expectation one or more would drop out. This last strategy occasionally backfired because the workload of shooting two models on the same day was too much for me if they actually both showed up.

Underwater

I’ve done a couple underwater shoots and they’re impossibly hard. This idea that everything is going to look amazing underwater very is misguided. First of all let’s talk about gravity and boobs. You wouldn’t think it but boobs need gravity. Ever see what happens when you pour water into a swimming pool. Yeah, that’s what happens to boobs underwater. Amorphous blobs. Not attractive.

Second of all smokers have poor lung capacity. I found this out the hard way when I asked the model to go underwater and by the time I took one shot, she was already surfacing.

And all of this is taking place in a pool. Let’s not even get into the next-level of difficulty when you go into open-water. Waves, wildlife, temperature… drowning. 

Oh and communication is impossible. She can’t see you and she sure as hell can’t hear you. Even if she could, there’s little guarantee she could execute what you’re asking. Especially if she’s got no lung capacity and doesn’t swim well.

Which is why I was fascinated with this image and the subsequent video generated by RunwayML. The original image is Stable Diffusion using the new XL model which I then fed into RunwayML’s image-to-video generator. Granted, the RunwayML video is very rough and maybe marginally better than KaiberAI or any of the other ones I’ve tried, but it gives you an idea of where we’re going with this whole thing.

The Impossible

What is the value of this tool (AI) if not to create the impossible?

Of course one could make an outstanding argument for using this tool to streamline and decrease the costs of creating these types of images in real life but that is more of a commercial consideration than an artistic consideration.

As an example, in 2016 I shot Lindsay Hancock in Malibu (reference image attached as the last photo) and as we were driving near her house we came across a neighbor’s house with an outside wall full of bougainvillea flowers. At the time I didn’t know what they were called but since then I’ve purchased several of these trees for my own house. I pulled the car over and decided in an instant, “Let’s shoot here”.

It’s been seven years since that shoot but the color from those flowers created an imprint that would resurface in this series I call “The Impossible”. Why is it called The Impossible? Well, to start I’ve never seen purple flowers growing out of the water. Even if they did you wouldn’t find a location that had this many of them. Furthermore, some of the images where the subject is underwater, completely defies the laws of fluid dynamics with there being a top surface and a bottom surface. And even if all of the aforementioned impossibilities were true, it would still be quite the task to assemble a team to execute these shots… particularly the ones underwater per my post yesterday (or the day before).

So to me (at least for the time being), the value of this tool is to create the impossible. To inspire. To open one’s imagination. To excite. I know it doesn’t replace human contact, but it’s not supposed to. It’s supposed to bridge the gap between what we could do and what we can’t do.

Proof positive that all these AI models were trained on anime, porn, and other fantasies. 

Though it is impressive. 

No model. No reference image. No Midjourney. All Stable Diffusion Dreamshaper XL and Photoshop. 

I almost didn’t post this. Honestly, I’m still torn over all this stuff. It’s an internal debate that I have to reconcile myself. It could also be AI fatigue as this past week has been incredibly intensive on the learning curve and my health has not been cooperating enough to let me keep up. So it could just be the fatigue talking. But it is understandable I would be conflicted by this technology since I was first and foremost a photographer and not a “prompter” (though that belittles the actual workflow).

Time will tell.

Ignite

What you don’t know is I had to draw in the missing leg under the dress. You know, sometimes legs they just turn up missing. 

Not sure what is exactly happening in this scene and even less sure what’s happening in the video. It starts to get farther and farther from the “point of inception” the more you iterate and layer in the same platform or across platforms. This whole “life is like a box of chocolates” is fun and all until I get frustrated that I’m not getting what I really want. 

It’s why ControlNet (and NSFW) is the critical difference between Stable Diffusion and Midjourney. This image was created with MJ5 a couple weeks ago. I’ve since kinda walked away from MJ save for the occasional curiosity of how SDXL models compare to MJ (closer but still not good enough). Regardless I’m always looking for more controls. Posing controls, composition, subject placement, even with all the controls of Stable Diffusion it’s still a far cry from reality… but then again this is just the beginning. As ControlNet gets better (first it needs to be repaired for XL) and tools like Latent Couple advance to better reliability, storytelling will advance as well. 

Until then yeah, AI is (kinda) like a box of chocolates… but I like chocolates 😂

AI pictures often remind me of the way I used to shoot as a first-year photographer. Square compositions where the subject is exactly in the middle, posing vertically (regardless standing or sitting), and the perspective is always at mid-level to the crop (meaning right in the middle between the top and the bottom of the subject). Overall super boring. Very little variety and kinda repetitive. 

And then there’s the lighting. So often the faces are poorly lit, with a steep main light casting harsh shadows in the eyes. I suspect that AI models were trained with porn or Instagram or just public domain stuff like Google Images. Regardless, the results are often disappointing to say the least.

Personally I like images that are a little more nuanced. A little less “bat over the head” and a little more layered. Shooting through reflections, prisms, a moment between poses, subject looking away, nothing contrived, nothing repeatable, more soft focus (I hate tack sharp), a pinch of voyeurism, with something in the foreground obstructing the subject, even better obscuring enough where I don’t have to use Photoshop to censor the nudity. My images often incorporate architecture, texture, nature… I love concrete, steel, glass, and occasionally metallic surfaces. I love negative space and stepping back to make my subject really small so you can truly appreciate the entire set/scene/backdrop. Most of all, I love skin tones. Most often from the specular highlights created by hard light… (my fav is direct sunlight) but I’ll take strong backlight or two opposing side lights. 

All of this is to agree with the gripes of most that at least for now, that the images generated AI are too often one-dimensional and worse, flat. Not just the dead-eye expressions but just lifeless and flat. Like how I used to shoot as a first-year photographer. And if it weren’t for the novelty of it all I’d already be bored out of my mind.

…burdens you can carry

There are things that you can not replace. Loved ones. Memories. Scents/smells.

And then there's the human element.

I had been deep in AI for about two months before taking this shoot with Olivia. Days before the shoot I realized the shoot had but one singular concept and purpose. Do what you can't with AI…

Boredom: Is AI Ready for Prime Time?

Boredom is a powerful tool.

In fact I wish my kids were bored more. They can't stand having "nothing to do". I suppose that makes me old. I remember entire summers where we had "nothing to do". We made up games like bowling with random objects and a soccer ball. I remember riding my bike for what felt like hours in the lobby of our apartment building (because it was too hot outside) and making up stories in my head about time travel and doing great things. I remember wondering what it'd be like to have to escape an apartment fire or an armed gunman from our 9th floor unit which is to say that I imagined having to climb around the railing of our balcony to escape into our neighbors' units… (continued at LUCIMAblog.blogspot.com clickable link in profile)

Arguing with Tony Stark about AI Replacing Humans

The following is an excerpt from the transcript:

CL: So we have ChatGPT and other AI tools these days. Let me get to the point. We now have AI text-to-image generators and I sense that the masses are very afraid of this new technology for fear that their jobs will be replaced by AI/bots/robots. What is your take on the matter?

TS: Look, fear is a natural response, but let's not lose our heads here. Technology has always been advancing, and yeah, sometimes it makes people nervous. But look at it this way: Al is just a tool. It's like a hammer, okay? You can use it to build a house or you can swing it around like a maniac. It all comes down to how we decide to use it. Sure, some jobs may be impacted by Al, just like some jobs were impacted by the industrial revolution. But that doesn't mean we throw in the towel and panic. We adapt, we innovate, and we find new ways to contribute. Think about it, we have unprecedented potential to enhance our creativity, improve efficiency, and push boundaries with Al at our side. What's important here is that we don't let fear dictate our actions. We've faced challenges before and we've always come out on top. So, let's embrace this new technology, explore its possibilities, and find ways to use it to our advantage. After all, I've always been a fan of pushing the envelope and leaving my mark on the world. Now, it's time for the rest of humanity to step up and do the same.

Red Rum

I’ve always loved beaches. Desolate, Cast Away-type beaches. In fact I found a few along the Malibu coast back when I lived in LA. I even surfed one on a south swell and it felt sketchy as hell since it was a rock bottom and I was out there with only one other surfer. 

But I’ve never been on a red sand beach. 

I’ve been on red sand desert beach and had always wished for a place where the water meets the red sand while kissed by the sun. And while I’m sure there are places like that in the world, I’d never shot on one myself. At summer draws to a close (is it even still summer?) I’d be happy to just shoot once more on the beach.
